    </p>
    <h3>Removing Waste</h3>
    <p>
        - If your cells are metabolically active they are always producing metabolic waste.<br>
        - The body must remove it to maintain homeostasis.<br>
        - The main waste products are:
        <ul>
            <li>Carbon dioxide (from respiration). This is removed because it combines with water in plasma to make carbonic acid, 
                which makes the blood acidic. If this gets too acidic, enzymes will denature. It is expelled through diffusion 
                from capillaries to alveoli and then exhalation.</li>
            <li>Urea (from the breakdown of excess amino acids in the liver). This is removed because 
                it is toxic in high concentrations. High concentrations in the blood is called uraemia. It can cause cell 
                death, interfere with some cell signalling, and damage nerves, as well as water retention.</li>
            <li>Water. Excess water causes fluid around cells to become hypotonic. This is removed through urine.</li>
        </ul>
    </p>
