    <h2>5.3.4 Hormones in human reproduction</h2>
    <p>
        - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iXswGsfeHJg">GCSE Biology Revision "The Menstrual Cycle"</a>
    </p>
    <p>
        - The menstrual cycle is regulated by four main hormones:
        <ul>
            <li>FSH: follicle-stimulating hormone; produced by the pituitary gland</li>
            <li>LH: luteinizing hormone; produced by the pituitary gland</li>
            <li>Oestrogen: the main female reproductive hormone. Produced by the ovaries</li>
            <li>Progesterone: Produced by the ovaries; maintains uterus lining.</li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <h3>Stages of the menstrual cycle</h3>
    <p>
        - Day <b>1</b>: FSH is secreted, this leads to the egg maturing in the ovary.<br>
        - Day <b>1</b>-6: Menstruation - uterus lining breaks down.<br>
        - Day <b>5</b>-7: FSH stimulates ovaries to produce oestrogen. As levels rises, this inhibits FSH production.
        Oestrogen stimulates repair of uterus lining.<br>
        - Day <b>7</b>-13: Profliteration - repair of the uterus lining.<br>
        - Day <b>14</b>: Oestrogen stimulates LH release. Oestrogen levels drop. 
        LH causes ovulation - mature egg released from the ovary.<br>
        - Day <b>15</b>+: The empty egg follicle stimulates the release of Progesterone.
        Progesterone maintains uterus lining. Potential pregnancy.<br>
        - Day <b>28</b> (well, 26-32): Menstruation starts again if no pregnancy.
    </p>
